featured_reviews.review_id:
The Mosque is beautifully maintained, with clean facilities for bathroom use and performing wudu (ritual ablution). However, it is perplexing why there is conflict among Muslims when we all share a belief in one Allah and His Prophet.

As a non-resident of this state, I arrived here for personal reasons and stayed in a hotel near the Mosque. Upon hearing the Azan, I attended the Mosque for Salah (prayer). Being a Muslim, I follow the practices mentioned in the Kitaab (referring to the books of Hadith, such as Bukhari and Muslim) which include Rafa-Ul-Yadeein (raising hands during prayer).

Surprisingly, after completing my Salah, a fellow Muslim from the Mosque warned me not to return and threatened physical harm, instructing me to go to another Mosque affiliated with the Ahle Hadees sect.

I don't know when we Muslims will understand the real meaning of Islam.

Therefore, the conclusion is that if you adhere to the Deobandi school of thought, you are welcome to pray there.
